Categories requires students to sort words (tiles) into two categories.||To set up this activity, enter a title for each of the two categories. The titles will display in a fixed position. Enter in items. These will display as randomized and draggable.

Crossword converts a word list into a crossword that students must solve.||To set up a crossword, enter in a word and a hint, which will be displayed to the students. Click on '+' to add new words. Click on 'Compile' to generate the crossword.

Dialog is a convenient way to display a conversation between two characters to students. Click on the audio icon to add audio.||To set up a dialog, click on the image fields to import images of characters. Type in text that will appear in a speech bubble.

Flashcard presents students with a question and, optionally, an image.||To set up a flashcard, enter in a question and import an image. Add more pages to add more flashcards. Flashcards automatically get removed from the deck when answered correctly.

A Gate will branch the program flow based on the performance of the student.||Click on the 'Pass' options button to set the branch options for a student who has matched or exceeded the pass score. Click on the 'Fail' button to set the branch options for a student who hasn't succeeded.
An Image Page dedicates a full page to one image. Use the Text page type if you would like to combine images with text.
This Interactive Image page type is a placeholder for future functionality. Do not use currently.

The Interview page presents student with information, such as an interview question, that the student must respond to by selecting one of three responses. The responses are judged.||Type in what the interviewer says. Type in three responses that are presented to students as options. Type in a value (in points) that students will receive for each option. The highest value will become the total score for this page.
The Journal page combines and presents all of the student entries from the long answer pages.||Student responses will be automatically collated and presented.

The Long Answer page presents students with a text area in which to key in a long response (a paragraph, for example).||Long answer responses are reported to the learning management system (SCORM report)and collated on the Journal Page. Students can then copy the Journal Page, paste into a Word document and submit to instructor.||Use the 'Heading' field to organize the responses in the Journal Page.

Matching requires students to match draggable words (tiles) with fixed-position words.||To set up this activity, enter in the fixed position items in the left column. Enter in the matching items in the right column. These will be randomly displayed to the student.

The Menu Page supports a very simple 1 to 4 item menu. Each item is linked to another page in the project.||For more sophisticated menus, use the Text Page and links. Links support both external web pages and internal project pages.

The Multiple Choice Page supports a question stem and 1 to 5 options or distractors.||Each distractor can be supplied with feedback text and, optionally, a branching option.||Indicate which answers are correct by checking the 'correct' checkboxes. Enter in a point value.||This page type supports True and False (just use two distractors), multiple choice and multiple select.

The Organizer Page has many uses. The simplest use is to fill in items that students must order (chronologically, geographically, logically, etc.)||Enter in text. Indicate correct order by filling in a number for position. Ignore the other fields.||Organizer will randomize the items so that students can order them.

This Multiple Choice question type supports a question stem and 1 to 5 options or distractors.||This page type also supports a variable-length paragraph that displays above the question stem.||Each distractor can be supplied with feedback text and, optionally, a branching option.||Indicate which answers are correct by checking the 'correct' checkboxes. Enter in a point value.

This Multiple Choice question type supports a question stem and 1 to 3 options or distractors that can be variable length.||Each distractor can be supplied with feedback text and, optionally, a branching option.||Indicate which answers are correct by checking the 'correct' checkboxes. Enter in a point value.

This Multiple Choice question type supports a question stem and 1 to 5 options or distractors.||This page type also supports an image.||Each distractor can be supplied with feedback text and, optionally, a branching option.||Indicate which answers are correct by checking the 'correct' checkboxes. Enter in a point value.
The Report Page causes information to be sent to the Learning Management System related to the student's performance.||Enter in additional information that you would like students to see.

The Short Answer Page challenges students to type in a short answer in response to a question.||Enter in the question and the correct answer. You may use a vertical bar to separate options.||If you are familiar with regular expressions, you can check the Reg Ex box and use regular expressions. The template help (Help > Template Help)gives you more information on regular expressions.

The Text Page displays text, images, and even MathML and embedded objects from Web 2.0 applications.||Optionally, insert widgets into pages. Widgets allow you to add multiple choice questions, short answer questions and, in the future, other types of widgets to the page. Look for the Widget Button on the HTML Editor tool bar.

The Tiles Page typically displays three columns and three rows of tiles. The tiles are ordered by their point value. Students select the tile to answer questions.||For each tile or question, fill in the category, number of points, question stem, etc. The tiles will be sorted by category (which must match exactly) as well as by number of points.

The Video Page supports YouTube videos, MediaSpace, and imported MP4 files.||For YouTube and MediaSpace videos paste in the URL in the first field. (Consult the General Help for MediaSpace directions). Otherwise click the 'Import Video' button. You can also import a captions file.

The Video Scenario Page supports YouTube videos, but in a unique way. This page presents students with a text description of a scenario. Students are given options on the best solution to the problem presented in the scenario. The video plays out the results of the student selection. Students earn the most points by making a good selection in their first or second try.||Type in a scenario description. Generate three or four options. Click the '+' button to add options. Type in feedback and paste in the YouTube URL for the video that matches the option.

The Wall Page stops the student from navigating to the next section of content. Students must 'branch' to the other side of the wall from any of the page types that support branching such as the Question Page or Gate.
